-- Reliance, Sintex, Mahindra, Tulip Telecom, Religare: India Equity Preview
-- Pooja Thakur
-- 2010-06-18T02:53:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-18/reliance-sintex-mahindra-tulip-telecom-religare-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 153.82, or 0.9 percent, to 17,616.69, the S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange rose 0.8 percent to
5,274.85 and the  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.7 percent to 2,224.10.
SGX CNX Nifty Index futures for June delivery fell 0.3 to
5,270.0 at 10:48 a.m. in Singapore.  
 Indian Oil Corp.  (IOCL IN): The nation’s second-biggest
refiner may consider issuing 10 percent of new shares that may
raise 80 billion rupees ($1.73 billion), MoneyControl said.
The stock gained 1.1 percent to 337.25 rupees.  
 Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd.  (MM IN): India’s biggest sport-
utility vehicle and tractor maker signed a joint venture
agreement with Arabia Holdings and Ras Al-Khaimah Transport
Investments LLC for armoring vehicles, it said in a statement to
the National Stock Exchange. The shares added 0.9 percent to
634.70 rupees.  
 Reliance Industries Ltd.  (RIL IN): India’s largest company
by market value should cede its rights to a petroleum
exploration block off India’s eastern coast, the Mint newspaper
reported, citing a recommendation to the government by the
Directorate of Hydrocarbons. The newspaper didn’t say where it
got the information. D.N. Narasimha Raju, a joint secretary at
the oil ministry, and a Reliance Industries spokesperson who
wasn’t identified declined to comment, according to the report.  
 Separately, Reliance may buy 26 percent of Pipavav Shipyard
Ltd., the Economic Times reported, citing market sources that it
didn’t identify. A Reliance Industries spokesperson declined to
comment, the newspaper said. The stock gained 1.3 percent to
1,071.40 rupees.  
 Religare Enterprises Ltd.  (RELG IN): The financial services
company plans to buy small or so-called boutique asset
management companies in the U.S. as part of its plans to grow
into a global financial services company that oversees as much
as $40 billion, the Financial Express reported, citing Chief
Executive Officer Shachindra Nath. The stock slumped 7 percent
to 393.20 rupees.  
 Sintex Industries Ltd.  (SINT IN): The engineering company
was rated “overweight” in new coverage by  Princy Singh  and
 Dinesh S. Harchandani , analysts at JPMorgan Chase & Co., who
said earnings may be “set for a strong rebound” as the company
benefits from infrastructure investments and government social-
spending initiatives. The analysts set a share-price estimate of
435 rupees. Sintex lost 1 percent to 294.90 rupees.  
 Tulip Telecom Ltd.  (TTSL IN): Qualcomm Inc.’s Indian unit,
which won permits to offer wireless broadband Internet services
in the country, may sell a stake to Tulip Telecom Ltd., the
Press Trust of India reported, without saying where it obtained
the information. Tulip fell 0.3 percent to 863.75 rupees.  
